Steve wrote:

>>The business of making exceptions is a dangerous one, but I feel
that Kolja and possibly Elde should probably be excepted, or at least
treated differently, when the above adjustment is made<<

Well, thank you for this friendly gesture - I would certainly
appreciate not being cut down to 0.5 VT or so. 

I share your dislike of exceptions, though, especially when they are
obviously tailored to individual players - they may be a good thing in
terms of motivating players or for fairness, but they just don't
"feel" right. Why not make the exception more generic: say, have a
similar exception phrase with "if the number of Voting Tokens
possessed by any player after the adjustment performed above in (3) is
less than 5, ...". This would at least sound more impartial (and it
would also accommodate other new players who might join Agora during
the voting period of this proposal).

By the way, you probably have discussed all this over and over again,
but concerning the strategy of "one-off rules": normally, rules do not
implement one-off effects, and they do not immedately change the game
state, they just provide the static framework within which play takes
place. Single changes of the game state, properties of entities etc
via proposal and vote are deliberately made difficult in the rules (I
guess in that sense the failure of RGBI was in accordance to the game
spirit). 

Now changing things via the formal trick of a self-repealing rule may
work, and be legal, but it somehow feels like sweeping a difficulty
under the rug. What do you think: is it part of a deliberate game
design that arbitrary changes to the game state cannot be made by
adopting a proposal (unless one circumvents that problem with the
clumsy device of a self-repealing rule), so something like RGBII goes
against the spirit of the game, or do we really want to allow such
changes, but we simply haven't yet gotten round to introducing a
loophole-free rule section for that, so we make do improvising within
the rules as they are?

Kolja A.

