Crito wrote:

>>Self-repealing rules seem as good or better a way of doing it as any
other, to me.  I would be interested in what your solution would be
that involves some kind of loophole-free rule section.<<

Well, naively I would think that something like RGBI should work:
simply propose that "when this proposal is adopted, the following
things happen:..." etc., where just about anything may be stated as
"...". 

And naively I would say Rule 594 (Proposals and Rule Changes) allows
exactly that.

Why did RGBI not work, anyway? It failed, and I must admit that I am
not quite aware of the detailed arguments why it did, but there must
be some reason :).

Now in general I can imagine that just making everything accessible to
changes due to "simple", non-rule proposals can lead to a whole lot of
trouble; that's why I said that allowing it would require some
loophole-proofing.

And in fact, it seems to be a rather general principle that many
important things in the game may only change in ways expressly
provided for by some rule; for example, I see this principle in

Rule 1011 Game Entities May Not Be Arbitrarily Changed
Rule 1513 Authority of Non-Rule Entities
Rule 1586 Definition and Continuity of Entities

The same principle of tying everything to some rule also appears
in many other places, like 

Rule 1728 Actions Without Objection
Rule 1467 Definition of a Currency
Rule 1469 Creation and Destruction of Treasuries
Rule 1472 Transfer of Currencies, esp. point c)
Rule 1596 Currency Transfers, generally

So the situation is this: the naive way, changing things be a mere
proposal, is not possible in spite of Rule 594; there must be a rule
involved. I suspect this limitation is there for a reason, maybe
because it is the only way to avoid lots of loopholes.

But then using self-repealing rules like RGBII seems to me to do - in
spirit - just such a change by mere proposal, while obeying - in form
- the principle that such changes are not allowed, and that a rule
must somehow be involved to make an arbitrary, one-off change.

And it is this tension that I don't quite understand yet - do you
consider this no problem at all, or "looks bad, but works", or "we
just haven't got round to doing it more elegantly, so we keep
improvising" or what?

Kolja A.

