> Well, naively I would think that something like RGBI should work:
> simply propose that "when this proposal is adopted, the following
> things happen:..." etc., where just about anything may be stated as
> "...". And naively I would say Rule 594 (Proposals and Rule Changes)
> allows exactly that.

That isn't so naive, in fact. Before a relatively recent reform,
Proposals had been permitted to contain only two things, Rule Changes
and Directives. You already know about Rule Changes; Directives were
the instruments whereby parts of the Game State other than the Rules
could be modified by a Proposal, and only those Directives that were
specifically authorized by the Rules could have any effect on those
parts of the Game State.

That recent Proposal Reform auhtorized Proposals to make arbitrary
changes to the Game State in the most general terms : that's what 
the language in 594, "implemented to the maximal extent permitted
by the Rules", is all about.

> Why did RGBI not work, anyway? It failed, and I must admit that I am
> not quite aware of the detailed arguments why it did, but there must
> be some reason :).

The reason why it failed is precisely that, rather than make arbitrary
changes to the Game State, it attempted to call upon the procedure of
Currency Transfers to effect a given set of 'monetary' changes. But
the Rules that govern Currency Transfers are quite clear on one point -
that for a Currency Transfer to be valid, there must be a Rule which
specifies a Player required to record (or "detect and report", as Game
Custom has it) that particular kind of Transfer.

RGBI clashed with that particular requirement; the Proposal itself
directed the Assessor to record the Transfers it called for, but that
was not sufficient - a Proposal is not a Rule. (There was also a second
problem with RGBI's attempt to call for Transfers, in that it wasn't
clear that even had Rule 1596 allowed a Proposal to specify a Player
to D&R the Transfers, Rule 594 would have been sufficient to authorize
a Proposal to effect those Transfers. But that question didn't have to
be addressed, as the D&R problem was, clearly, enough to make RGBI fail.)

> Now in general I can imagine that just making everything accessible to
> changes due to "simple", non-rule proposals can lead to a whole lot of
> trouble; that's why I said that allowing it would require some
> loophole-proofing.

Actually, the intent of the aforementioned Proposal reform was to bring
about just such a situation; it was adopted, presumably, because it was
felt that the Rules contained sufficient safeguards against abuse of the
procedure. The prevalent argument, IIRC, is that there's nothing that can
be done with a Proposal with the current 594 that couldn't be done
previously with a Proposal enacting one or more self-repealing Rules.

> And it is this tension that I don't quite understand yet - do you
> consider this no problem at all, or "looks bad, but works", or "we
> just haven't got round to doing it more elegantly, so we keep
> improvising" or what?

Well, the answer to that, I think, is that a self-repealing Rule can,
nevertheless, do things that a Proposal implementing arbitrary Game
State changes cannot do. For instance, it's far from clear that a
Proposal can have lasting effects, or impose obligations upon Players.
Various arguments can be made for and against the effectiveness of
all but the first of the following Proposal provisions :

   When this Proposal is adopted, every Player's VT holdings shall be
   set to 0.

   When this Proposal is adopted, every Player shall be required to
   donate all VTs to the Bank As Soon As Possible.

   For ten days after this Proposal is adopted, no Player may possess
   any VTs.

   When this Proposal is adopted, all Players shall be awarded the
   Patent Title of Nothinghead.

   There are Entities known as Happy Pills; whenever a Player, for
   any reason, holds no Happy Pills, he receives one.

   The Nomic Century begins on the first day of any year, the last two
   digits of which are "00", and lasts for one hundred years.

All of these provisions would be controversial to some degree, IMHO,
because what they attempt to "do" is usually regarded as the exclusive
province of the Rules : impose requirements, specify a duration, create
Entities, define new terms...

I think your perception of a "tension" here derives from the fact that
the current form of Rule 594 muddles the dividing line between Rules and
Proposals. One of the reasons why the last Proposal Reform was successful
was that Directives were generally considered useless and mostly broken.

Personally, I think it could be quite useful to model a multi-tiered
Proposal system after real-world law, and institute a graded series
of Game-State-changing instruments including Directives (changing,
like the Directives of old, specific and restricted parts of the Game
State), Orders (imposing requirements on Players), Decrees (with
authority to create or define Entities), Proposals (changing Rules),
Constitutional Amendments, etc. These could be used to bring about
the much-talked-about extension to Officer's powers.


