"Laurent" == Laurent Bossavit <morendil@micronet.fr> writes:

Laurent> Well, the answer to that, I think, is that a self-repealing
Laurent> Rule can, nevertheless, do things that a Proposal
Laurent> implementing arbitrary Game State changes cannot do. For
Laurent> instance, it's far from clear that a Proposal can have
Laurent> lasting effects, or impose obligations upon Players.  Various
Laurent> arguments can be made for and against the effectiveness of
Laurent> all but the first of the following Proposal provisions :

Laurent>    When this Proposal is adopted, every Player's VT holdings
Laurent> shall be set to 0.

Would succeed.

Laurent>    When this Proposal is adopted, every Player shall be
Laurent> required to donate all VTs to the Bank As Soon As Possible.

IMO, would fail, presently.  Players are not obligated to abide by
Proposals.

Laurent>    For ten days after this Proposal is adopted, no Player may
Laurent> possess any VTs.

I'm not sure on this one.

Laurent>    When this Proposal is adopted, all Players shall be
Laurent> awarded the Patent Title of Nothinghead.

I think this would succeed.

Laurent>    There are Entities known as Happy Pills; whenever a
Laurent> Player, for any reason, holds no Happy Pills, he receives
Laurent> one.

I would interpret this to award a Happy Pill to everyone who does not
have a Happy Pill _at the time the proposal was adopted_, but
otherwise have no effect.

Laurent>    The Nomic Century begins on the first day of any year, the
Laurent> last two digits of which are "00", and lasts for one hundred
Laurent> years.

Would have no substantial effect, although it might influence game
custom.

Laurent> All of these provisions would be controversial to some
Laurent> degree, IMHO, because what they attempt to "do" is usually
Laurent> regarded as the exclusive province of the Rules : impose
Laurent> requirements, specify a duration, create Entities, define new
Laurent> terms...

I've considered suggesting a provision allowing a Proposal to
establish obligations (with limitations).  I don't think it would be
all that hard to do.


