Klaus Herrmanns NB6_25 (3751) writes:
>
>Now changing things via the formal trick of a self-repealing rule may
>work, and be legal, but it somehow feels like sweeping a difficulty
>under the rug. What do you think: is it part of a deliberate game
>design that arbitrary changes to the game state cannot be made by
>adopting a proposal (unless one circumvents that problem with the
>clumsy device of a self-repealing rule), so something like RGBII goes
>against the spirit of the game, or do we really want to allow such
>changes, but we simply haven't yet gotten round to introducing a
>loophole-free rule section for that, so we make do improvising within
>the rules as they are?

As the author of RGB I & II, I can tell you that I regard the form
that RGB II takes as a self-repealing Rule as a regrettably inelegant
necessity. The point of the most recent reform of the Proposal system
(see P3445, adopted Mar 26, 1997) was precisely to allow these kinds
of game state changes without the need to enact self-repealing Rules.
RGB I attempted to exploit this possibility, but ran into technical
difficulties, for details of which see the Judgement of CFJ 928.
The failure of RGB I has made me wary: a similar failure of RGB II
to be effective on technical grounds would be personally rather
embarrassing. Additionally, the conceptual terrain in the area of
currency transfers is about to be transformed by 'Pragmatic Currencies',
which in my opinion makes it even more likely that I would make a
mistake if I tried to finesse this and do it as elegantly as might
be possible. Once bitten, twice shy, I guess: RGB II is a little
inelegant, but it's pretty safe. Having said that, I have tried to
make RGB II as elegant as I can within the constraints I have chosen.

It's an interesting question how the Proposal reform enacted by P3445
will interact with the Currency reform currently being voted on as
P3533. Aside from the list of provisions of controversial effectiveness
given by Morendil, there's the question of whether wholesale changes
to Currency holdings can easily be achieved as Transfers in the
Pragmatic Currencies framework. I take it, for instance, that it would
be pretty messy (although perfectly legal) for a Proposal to create
a large number of Transfer Orders (in the case of RGB II, one for
every Player, another one for every Contestmaster, and a few others),
which individual Players would then have to satisfy by making the
appropriate Payment Orders. Too much work for the Assessor, I reckon.
The alternative might be to have the Proposal give a once-off authority
to the Assessor, or the Chancellor, to satisfy Transfer Orders without
the consent of the Players (basically a form of asset-seizing). But
I'm not sure if a Proposal can do that under the new system, which is
one of the reasons I decided to frame RGB II in the form of
adjustments rather than Transfers.

